<title>Project: A Clever Sundial</title>

<project xml:id="project-trig-sundial">
	<title>How Tall is the Gnomon?</title>

<introduction>
	<p>Sundials are one of the oldest types of clocks. Because the apparent motion of the sun through the sky defines time for us, the position of a shadow is an obvious way to measure that progress. One common type of sundial has a vertical object, called a <term>gnomon</term>, standing in the middle of a circle. If the circle is oriented correctly one edge of the gnomon's shadow cross the number marking the time. </p>
	<p>We also notice that the sun rises and sets at different times throughout the year and that its path across the sky changes. In particular the sun is much higher in the sky in summer and lower in winter. This change is especially noticable in the far north and far south of the planet. </p>
	<p>In this project we calculate the effect of the shifting path on shadow length and consider ways to adjust for that. This is accomplished using simple trigonometric calculations.</p>
</introduction>

